{{Distinguish|Lowry Air Force Base{{!}}Weld County's "High Frequency Radar Station Site" (FUDS property B08CO0494)}} <!-- http://www.gao.gov/gao-01-1012sp/CO.html --> '''Genesee Mountain Park Training Annex''' (1955–70) is a [[Formerly Used Defense Site]] (# B08CO0493)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gao.gov/gao-01-1012sp/CO.html|title=U.S. General Accounting Office|publisher=}}</ref> of {{Convert|3|acre|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jeffco.us/placenames/search2.cfm?Find=genese|title=Jefferson County, Colorado - Place Names Directory|publisher=}}</ref> at [[Genesee Park (Colorado)]]<ref name=Mueller>{{Cite report |last=Mueller |first=Robert |year=1989 |title=Air Force Bases |url=http://www.afhso.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-100921-026.pdf |volume=Volume I: Active Air Force Bases Within the United States of America on 17 September 1982 |publisher=Office of Air Force History |isbn=0-912799-53-6 |page=600 |accessdate=2013-08-15}}</ref> used as a [[Lowry Air Force Base]] radar station for training. Early in the [[Cold War]], Lowry AFB supported [[Strategic Air Command]] nuclear bomber training (e.g., [[B-47]], [[B-52]], etc.) with [[United States automatic tracking radar stations|automatic tracking radar (autotrack)]] and by January 1962, the "Tactical Missile School at Lowry" conducted [[Matador missile]] training "in the Black Hangar"<ref>{{Cite web |format=military newsgroup |date=June 14, 2010 |title=Matador and Mace Tactical Missile Veterans |url=http://www.tacmissileers.org/guestbook/ |accessdate=2013-03-18 |quote=Dennis Schneider Wed, February 8, 2012 2:01 PM I was assigned to the Tactical Missile School at Lowry AFB…in Jan 1962. Upon graduation in June…I received orders assigning us to instructor duty in that very school, which was located in the Black Hangar … at Lowry…from Jan 1962 - Dec 1963…I {{sic|tought}}…in the TAC Missile Maintenance training program.}} (message 1060)</ref> (the [[surface-to-surface missile]] used [[Matador Automatic Radar Control]] for autotrack.) Automatic tracking radar was also used in [[Korean War]] [[ground-directed bombing]] training for live bomb drops at ranges like the [[Lowry Bombing and Gunnery Range]] (the early 1960s [[Titan 1]] sites near Denver also had tracking radars in a "guidance facility".)<ref>asuwlink.uwyo.edu/~jimkirk/Lowry1A.doc</ref>
==Denver Bomb Plot== The '''Denver Bomb Plot''' was the call sign of an early [[Cold War]] automatic tracking radar station established for training and evaluation by August 25, 1949.<ref name=Schlupp>{{Citation |format=letter |last=Schlupp |first=Capt John A |date=25 August 1949 |title=Radar Activity |url=http://www.fold3.com/image/#6312792 |publisher=Detachment A, [[1st Combat Evaluation Group|3903rd Radar Bomb Squadron]] |accessdate=2012-07-23 |quote=Two (2) cys Itr, Det A 39030[sic] Radar Bomb Scoring Sq, Lowry AF Base, 25 Aug 49}}</ref> The station was operated by Detachment A of the [[3903rd Radar Bomb Scoring Squadron]], was commanded by Capt John A. Schlupp in 1949,{{r|Schlupp}} and conducted [[Radar Bomb Scoring]] of simulated bomb drops on mock Denver area targets by [[Strategic Air Command]] aircrews, including those of the 1955 [[1st Combat Evaluation Group#Fairchild Trophy|SAC Bombing and Navigation Competition]] which included simulated [[bomber stream]] attacks on November 9, 15, 23, & 26.<ref>http://www.7bwb-36assn.org/b36genhistpg4.html</ref> In 1959 the detachment moved 4 trailers,<ref name=DN1995>{{Cite news |date=February 21, 1995 |title=Townsfolk Hope to Shoot Down Military's Bombing-Range Plans |url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/405724/TOWNSFOLK-HOPE-TO-SHOOT-DOWN-MILITARYS-BOMBING-RANGE-PLANS.html?pg=all |newspaper=[[Deseret News]] |accessdate=2012-07-06}}</ref> after being designated Detachment 1, [[11th Radar Bomb Scoring Squadron]]; to the [[La Junta Radar Bomb Scoring Site]] at the former WWII [[La Junta Army Airfield]] (122 people on 6 acres in FY1984).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dod.mil/pubs/foi/administration_and_Management/admin_matters/192.pdf|title=ALERT|publisher=dod.mil}}</ref>
